<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="assets/xml/rss.xsl" media="all"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Colour Science</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/</link><description>Colour: Colour Science for Python</description><atom:link href="https://www.colour-science.org/rss.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><language>en</language><copyright>Contents © 2020 &lt;a href="mailto:colour-developers@colour-science.org"&gt;Colour Developers&lt;/a&gt; </copyright><lastBuildDate>Sat, 25 Jan 2020 09:01:11 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>Nikola (getnikola.com)</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>Colour 0.3.15 is available!</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0315-is-available/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour/releases/tag/v0.3.15"&gt;Colour 0.3.15&lt;/a&gt;
is available!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0315-is-available/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (1 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>colour</category><category>colour science</category><category>release</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0315-is-available/</guid><pubDate>Sat, 25 Jan 2020 08:44:09 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>PyCharm, Vagrant, Ansible &amp; Poetry</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/pycharm-vagrant-ansible-poetry/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;div class="alert alert-dismissible alert-info line-block"&gt;
&lt;div class="line"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Note&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="line"&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="line"&gt;This post is an update to the
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/pycharm-vagrant-fabric-anaconda/"&gt;PyCharm, Vagrant, Fabric &amp;amp; Anaconda&lt;/a&gt; post.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Installing the whole development toolchain for &lt;strong&gt;Colour&lt;/strong&gt; roughly means
deploying:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class="simple"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.python.org/download/releases/"&gt;Python&amp;gt;=2.7&lt;/a&gt; or
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.python.org/download/releases/"&gt;Python&amp;gt;=3.5&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://imageio.github.io/"&gt;Imageio&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.scipy.org/"&gt;SciPy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/six/"&gt;Six&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://networkx.github.io/"&gt;NetworkX&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/OpenImageIO/oiio"&gt;OpenImageIO&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pandas.pydata.org/"&gt;Pandas&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://matplotlib.org/"&gt;Matplotlib&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.graphviz.org/"&gt;Graphviz&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pygraphviz.github.io/"&gt;PyGraphviz&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/biblib-simple/"&gt;biblib-simple&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/coverage/"&gt;Coverage.py&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/coveralls/"&gt;coveralls&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/flake8/"&gt;Flake8&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.pyinvoke.org/"&gt;Invoke&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://jupyter.org/"&gt;Jupyter&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/mock/"&gt;mock&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://nose.readthedocs.io/en/latest"&gt;nose&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pre-commit.com/"&gt;pre-commit&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://docs.pytest.org/en/latest/"&gt;pytest&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/twolfson/restructuredtext-lint"&gt;restructuredtext-lint&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://sphinx-doc.org"&gt;Sphinx&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/rtfd/sphinx_rtd_theme/"&gt;sphinx_rtd_theme&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://sphinxcontrib-bibtex.readthedocs.io/"&gt;sphinxcontrib-bibtex&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/twine/"&gt;twine&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/google/yapf"&gt;YAPF==0.23.0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;... and too many things I just don't remember!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I decided to see how I could make that setup a bit more portable and easier to
deploy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That's where &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.vagrantup.com/"&gt;Vagrant&lt;/a&gt; kicks in along
&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.jetbrains.com/pycharm/"&gt;PyCharm&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.ansible.com/"&gt;Ansible&lt;/a&gt;
and &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://poetry.eustace.io"&gt;Poetry&lt;/a&gt;!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The following guide assume that you have that you have &lt;em&gt;PyCharm&lt;/em&gt; installed and
are using &lt;em&gt;macOS&lt;/em&gt;, although it should pretty much be platform agnostic.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/pycharm-vagrant-ansible-poetry/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (5 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>ansible</category><category>poetry</category><category>pycharm</category><category>vagrant</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/pycharm-vagrant-ansible-poetry/</guid><pubDate>Sat, 09 Nov 2019 02:46:40 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>NumFOCUS, Colour 0.3.14 and Colour - Datasets 0.1.0!</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/numfocus-colour-0314-and-colour-datasets-010/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;We are delighted to announce that &lt;strong&gt;Colour&lt;/strong&gt; has joined the
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://numfocus.org/"&gt;NumFOCUS&lt;/a&gt;  affiliated projects and that
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour/releases/tag/v0.3.14"&gt;Colour 0.3.14&lt;/a&gt;
has been released over the weekend along with
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour-datasets/releases/tag/v0.1.0"&gt;Colour - Datasets 0.1.0&lt;/a&gt;,
a new &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.python.org/"&gt;Python&lt;/a&gt; package dedicated to colour science
datasets management.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/numfocus-colour-0314-and-colour-datasets-010/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (4 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/numfocus-colour-0314-and-colour-datasets-010/</guid><pubDate>Sun, 27 Oct 2019 08:39:18 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>sRGB EOTF: Pure Gamma 2.2 Function or Piece-Wise Function?</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/srgb-eotf-pure-gamma-22-or-piece-wise-function/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;A topic that caused a great deal of
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.liftgammagain.com/forum/index.php?threads/dealing-with-srgb.13239/"&gt;passionate&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://twitter.com/troy_s/status/1170094480080265217"&gt;discussions&lt;/a&gt; is that
of the &lt;em&gt;sRGB&lt;/em&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Electro-Optical Transfer Function&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;strong&gt;EOTF&lt;/strong&gt;): Should it be
the &lt;em&gt;pure Gamma 2.2 function&lt;/em&gt; or the &lt;em&gt;piece-wise function&lt;/em&gt; defined in
&lt;em&gt;IEC 61966-2-1:1999 Standard&lt;/em&gt;?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/srgb-eotf-pure-gamma-22-or-piece-wise-function/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (4 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>colour</category><category>colour science</category><category>EOTF</category><category>sRGB</category><category>transfer function</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/srgb-eotf-pure-gamma-22-or-piece-wise-function/</guid><pubDate>Fri, 25 Oct 2019 19:54:39 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Colour 0.3.13 is available!</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0313-is-available/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour/releases/tag/v0.3.13"&gt;Colour 0.3.13&lt;/a&gt;
is available!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0313-is-available/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (1 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>colour</category><category>colour science</category><category>release</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0313-is-available/</guid><pubDate>Sat, 20 Apr 2019 03:37:15 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Colour 0.3.12 and Colour - Checker Detection 0.1.0!</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0312-colour-checker-detection-010/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;After over a year of work, &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour/releases/tag/v0.3.12"&gt;Colour 0.3.12&lt;/a&gt;
is finally released. &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour-checker-detection/releases/tag/v0.1.0"&gt;Colour - Checker Detection 0.1.0&lt;/a&gt;
is also available.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0312-colour-checker-detection-010/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (2 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>colour</category><category>colour - checker detection</category><category>colour science</category><category>release</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0312-colour-checker-detection-010/</guid><pubDate>Sun, 24 Mar 2019 03:47:21 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Anders Langlands - Render Color Spaces</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/anders-langlands-render-color-spaces/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;p&gt;Courtesy of Anders Langlands, we are hosting the
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.colour-science.org/anders-langlands"&gt;Render Color Spaces&lt;/a&gt; page
that was formerly available at
&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.anderslanglands.com/blog//2016/06/23/render-color-space.html"&gt;www.anderslanglands.com&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/anders-langlands-render-color-spaces/</guid><pubDate>Wed, 22 Aug 2018 08:55:53 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Colour 0.3.11 is available!</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0311-is-available/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;We are pleased to announce that &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour/releases/tag/v0.3.11"&gt;Colour 0.3.11&lt;/a&gt;
is available!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0311-is-available/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (1 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>colour</category><category>colour science</category><category>release</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0311-is-available/</guid><pubDate>Sun, 18 Feb 2018 10:28:42 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>The Road to Stable</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/the-road-to-stable/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Colour has been in public development for over 3 years. The package has grown in various directions since the initial release and offers a significant amount of &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.colour-science.org/features/"&gt;features&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It is used in research groups such as the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://sachi.cs.st-andrews.ac.uk/"&gt;St Andrews HCI Research Group&lt;/a&gt; or companies like &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.google.com/"&gt;Google&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merck_Group"&gt;Merck KGaA&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.moving-picture.com/"&gt;The Moving Picture Company&lt;/a&gt;. Even though it has reached a certain stability and maturity, it is still in alpha development status.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Two important features are missing for a first feature complete stable release:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class="simple"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;The first one is that our current dictionary based spectral implementation has reached its limits when building support for Machado et al. (2010): attempting to alter the domain or range of a &lt;cite&gt;SpectralPowerDistribution&lt;/cite&gt; is difficult. With that in mind, we have started to work on a new alternative implementation where data is exposed as a continuous function modeled using an interpolating function encapsulated within an extrapolating function: &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour/issues/335"&gt;#335&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;The second is support for metadata inside the API. Most of the codebase adopts definitions/functions over classes to stay clean and lean, the aforementioned spectral implementation being a notable exception. As a consequence, it is hard to implement a non-intrusive classifying mechanism, provide usable hints on functions domain/range or create an auto-conversion layer. We have considered multiple ways of providing the necessary metadata, e.g. &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour/branches/all"&gt;experimental/medatada* branches&lt;/a&gt;, and decided that the true elegant solution was through docstrings.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The following example showcases the current implementation, defining metadata for &lt;em&gt;parameters&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;returns&lt;/em&gt; and the definition by using the &lt;em&gt;notes&lt;/em&gt; section:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre class="code python"&gt;&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-1"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="k"&gt;def&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nf"&gt;luminance_Newhall1943&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;V&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;):&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-2"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;    &lt;span class="sd"&gt;"""&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-3"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    Returns the *luminance* :math:`R_Y` of given *Munsell* value :math:`V`&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-4"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    using *Newhall et al. (1943)* method.&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-5"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-6"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    Parameters&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-7"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    ----------&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-8"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    V : numeric or array_like&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-9"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;        metadata : {'type': 'Munsell Value', 'symbol': 'V', 'extent': (0, 10)}&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-10"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;        *Munsell* value :math:`V`.&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-11"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-12"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    Returns&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-13"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    -------&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-14"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    numeric or array_like&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-15"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;        metadata : {'type': 'Luminance', 'symbol': 'R_Y', 'extent': (0, 100)}&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-16"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;        *luminance* :math:`R_Y`.&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-17"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-18"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    Notes&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-19"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    -----&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-20"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    metadata : {'classifier': 'Luminance Conversion Function', 'method_name':&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-21"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;        'Newhall 1943', 'method_strict_name': 'Newhall et al. (1943)'}&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-22"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-23"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    References&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-24"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    ----------&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-25"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    .. [1]  Newhall, S. M., Nickerson, D., &amp;amp; Judd, D. B. (1943). Final report&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-26"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;            of the OSA subcommittee on the spacing of the munsell colors. JOSA,&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-27"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;            33(7), 385. doi:10.1364/JOSA.33.000385&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-28"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-29"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    Examples&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-30"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    --------&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a name="rest_code_de5b7aecb6f8486ea6dc769d9368378f-31"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="sd"&gt;    &amp;gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt; luminance_Newhall1943(3.74629715382)  # doctest: +ELLIPSIS&lt;/span&gt;
